        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your marginal rate is the rate that applies to the next dollar you earn — it's set by whichever federal and provincial bracket the top slice of your income falls into. Your average rate is simply total income tax divided by gross income, expressed as a percentage. Canada uses a graduated bracket system, so only the income above each threshold is taxed at the higher rate — not your entire income. For most people, the marginal rate is noticeably higher than the average rate.",
